40|$|This study {{extends the}} {{traditional}} set of central bank's interventions to include official announcements {{in order to}} provide empirical evidence on two pivotal questions: (i) are FX authorities able to influence market expectations with different instruments? (ii) how should interventions be designed to have the greatest impact? Using Japanese data over 1992 - 2004 and an event-study approach, we estimate the effect of different strategies on the USD/JPY exchange-rate risk-neutral density. Overall, <b>transparent</b> <b>policies</b> (public and oral interventions) appear to be the most effective. Moreover, the effect is greater when policies involve a financial cost (risk) suggesting that simple announcements can only be deemed as an imperfect substitute for actual interventions. Central bank interventions Event studies Communication policy Risk-neutral density...|$|E
